  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 15.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The mount of the Amalekites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This name points to some incident of which the memory is lost, though, with the usual tenacity of names, the name which once recorded it survives. It may have been some ancient settlement of the Amalekites, who were a very wandering, wide-spread race, which gave the name; or it may have been some great defeat and slaughter which they suffered from the Israelites, whose land they invaded (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 6:3, 33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), just as the rock Oreb and the wine-press of Zeeb (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 7:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") commemorated the victory over those princes. ",
        "children": []
      },
